abstract: >-
  A personal essay collection and structured knowledge graph mapping the three
  major Buddhist Abhidharma traditions (Theravāda, Sarvāstivāda, Yogācāra) onto
  contemporary frameworks in computational phenomenology — predictive processing,
  active inference, Global Workspace Theory, Parallel Distributed Processing, and
  related approaches. Comprises ten essays (five themes × English + Japanese), a
  cross-tradition dharma comparison table (~130 dharmas across nine sheets), and
  a JSON-LD knowledge graph (~238 nodes, schema.org + custom vocabulary) with
  bilingual labels and Sanskrit / Pāli / Chinese philological alignment. An
  interactive 2D/3D viewer is provided. Developed in collaboration with the
  Claude language model (Anthropic) for synthesis, cross-tradition mapping, and
  graph encoding; the author retains responsibility for all claims.
